<DOC><DOCNO> AP890624-0126 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-24-89 2005EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Riot     06-24 0245</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Britain-Riot,0254</SECOND><HEAD>Right-Wing, Minority Groups Rally; Youths Go On Rampage</HEAD><DATELINE>DEWSBURY, England (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Rock-throwing youths battled with policeSaturday after rallies by a minority workers' group and theright-wing British National Party. Two officers were injured and 79demonstrators were arrested, authorities said.   Police, anticipating clashes between the groups, deployed morethan 700 officers and the government banned marches that were tohave followed the rallies that drew a total of about 400 people.   Police ringed the rally sites of the National Party and a localorganization of workers from the Indian and Pakistani community inthis city 180 miles northwest of London. Mounted officers, doghandlers and riot squads carrying shields and wearing helmets stoodby.   The clashes occurred after the rallies when police moved in toclear the town center of demonstrators. A police statement reportedno fights between the groups but that youths broke windows andseverely vandalized a pub.   Police estimated 250 people attended the workers' rally. TheBritish National Party supporters, estimated by police at 150, helda half-hour meeting and most left town in buses. The National Partyis a small, white neo-Nazi organization.   A police spokesman said that after the rallies, groups of youngpeople in the town center threw rocks and other objects at police.Officers carrying shields were sent into the area.   Youths set off a smoke bomb and attempted to barricade one road,police said. Nineteen cases of vandalism were reported, they said.</TEXT></DOC>